extracted_characteristics.life_cycle_stages:
Development lifecycle of the model‑driven DT framework proceeds in four key phases:
(1) BIM‑enrichment – the Building Control Engineer models sensors, actuators, and controllers within the BIM environment, yielding a semantically rich representation;
(2) MDE extraction – Model‑Driven Engineering principles automatically transform the enriched BIM into a structured digital representation (e.g., graph‑based or JSON schema) that preserves topology, control logic, and data flow;
(3) Artifact generation and deployment – the framework synthesizes deployable DT artefacts such as micro‑services, data pipelines, and visualization dashboards, through a minimal‑manual, template‑based pipeline;
(4) Runtime operation and evolution – real‑time data exchange (e.g., MQTT or WebSocket) synchronizes the twin with the physical building, while the modular architecture and standardized extension points allow the DT Engineer to inject custom analytics or control services.
Governance across these stages is codified by the defined stakeholder roles – Building Control Engineer (modeling), Facility Manager (monitoring & control), and DT Engineer (service extension).
